ord Arundel and Sampford Brett (both Somerset), and Sandford (Shropshire). See also   Sandiford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Samford","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Sandford  ."]},{"name":"Sanderford","meanings":["English: variant of   Sandford  ."]},{"name":"Sanford","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Sandford  ."]},{"name":"Sandiford","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Sandifer  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert De Sandford II was born in 1100, in Askham, Westmorland, England, his father, Gamel de Sandford, was 31 and his mother, Mrs. Gamel de Sandford, was 18. He married Wennisa De Askham in 1123, in Askham, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom. Th